    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-03-20T11:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-03-20T11:00:00-05:00" n="42"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d42">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72114/3413</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Switzerland</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_SPA1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Stovall</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Berne</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-03-20T17:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 20, 1918, 5 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received March 23, 2.05 a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2902. Information received from German Army administration, dated February 6,
                    through Spanish Embassy, Berlin, states captured soldiers and sailors can wear
                    either uniform provided by own Government, or clothing furnished for prisoners
                    by German Government, consisting of cap, coat, trousers, overcoat of dark color,
                    necktie, and footwear. Clothing must be marked with stripe of brood [<hi
                        rend="italic">khaki?</hi>] material 10 centimeters wide on left upper arm of
                    coat, stripe 5 centimeters wide on seams of trousers, and band on cap. Military
                    prisoners may also wear civilian clothing of black material sent from home if
                    materials as stated. Appropriate clothing provided for special occupations. No
                    particular uniform required for civilian prisoners. Every prisoner wear own
                    personal clothing. These regulations clothing noted in connection with uniforms
                    to be sent to Berne for American prisoners.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SPA1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Stovall</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
